{
  "nbformat": 4,
  "nbformat_minor": 5,
  "metadata": {
    "kernelspec": {
      "name": "maxima",
      "display_name": "Maxima",
      "language": "maxima"
    },
    "aximar": {}
  },
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "# 05 — Modelica Standard Library\n\nThe Modelica Standard Library (MSL) ships ~1500 components across electrical, mechanical, rotational, translational, thermal, fluid, and signal-processing domains. Every component is professionally-maintained, unit-checked, and documented. Building plants out of MSL components — rather than hand-rolling our own `Resistor.mo`, `Capacitor.mo`, etc. — is what most working control engineers want from a Modelica tool.\n\nmochi resolves cross-package references like `Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Basic.Resistor` by passing rumoca's `--source-root` through. As long as MSL is reachable from `MODELICAPATH` (the standard Modelica-tools env var, defined in [MLS §13.2.4](https://specification.modelica.org/master/packages.html#mapping-package-class-structures-to-a-hierarchical-file-system)) — or your machine has OpenModelica installed — `mod_load` works on MSL-using files transparently.\n\nThis notebook walks through:\n\n1. Where mochi looks for MSL.\n2. Loading a plant built from MSL components (an RC filter).\n3. Verifying it produces identical dynamics to the hand-rolled `RCFilter.mo`.\n4. Multi-domain modelling: a DC motor combining `Modelica.Electrical.Analog` and `Modelica.Mechanics.Rotational`.\n5. The known limitation around `Modelica.Blocks` linearisation.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "load(\"../../mochi.mac\")$\nload(\"numerics\")$\nload(\"ax-plots\")$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 51,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 1. Source-root discovery\n\n`mod_source_roots()` returns the directories rumoca will search for cross-package references. Resolution rules — explicit configuration always wins:\n\n1. `mod_set_source_root(path1, path2, ...)` or `mod_add_source_root(path)` set programmatically from Maxima.\n2. Otherwise, the `MODELICAPATH` environment variable (multi-path: colon-separated on Unix, semicolon-separated on Windows).\n3. Otherwise, fall back to OpenModelica's `$OPENMODELICAHOME/lib/omlibrary/Modelica*/` — the one tool-managed location widely deployed on Unix systems.\n\nThe cell below abbreviates each path's first two segments (the home-prefix dir like `Users` or `home`, and the username) to `.../` so the rendered notebook doesn't bake in the author's home directory. Run the bare `mod_source_roots()` on your own install to see the literal paths.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "map(lambda([p], sconcat(\".../\", simplode(rest(split(p, \"/\"), 2), \"/\"))),\n    mod_source_roots());",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 52,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "text/latex": [
              "\\left[ \\mbox{ .../.modelica/library/Modelica } \\right] "
            ]
          },
          "execution_count": 52,
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "execute_result"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "(If that's empty, set `MODELICAPATH` in your shell or use `mod_set_source_root` — see the README's *Prerequisites → Modelica Standard Library* section. The rest of this notebook needs MSL reachable from one of those.)",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 2. RC filter, MSL edition\n\n`examples/msl/RCFilterMSL.mo` is the same RC plant as `examples/RCFilter.mo`, but composed from MSL components rather than hand-rolled ones:\n\n```modelica\nmodel RCFilterMSL\n  Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Basic.Resistor   r1(R = 1.0);\n  Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Basic.Capacitor  c1(C = 0.5);\n  Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Basic.Ground     gnd;\n  Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Sources.SignalVoltage src;\n  input  Real Vin;\n  output Real Vcap;\nequation\n  src.v = Vin;\n  Vcap  = c1.v;\n  connect(src.p, r1.p);\n  connect(r1.n,  c1.p);\n  connect(c1.n,  gnd.p);\n  connect(src.n, gnd.p);\nend RCFilterMSL;\n```\n\nNo connector class, no `partial model OnePort` base — those live in `Modelica.Electrical.Analog.Interfaces`, and rumoca pulls them in via `--source-root`. Each MSL `Resistor` / `Capacitor` already extends MSL's `OnePort`, which extends MSL's connector — the whole chain just works.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "m_msl : mod_load(\"../msl/RCFilterMSL.mo\")$\nmod_print(m_msl)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 53,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Model:  RCFilterMSL\n  parameters:\n              [[r1_useHeatPort,false],[r1_R,1.0],[r1_T_ref,300.15],\n               [r1_alpha,0],[c1_C,0.5],[r1_T,r1_T_ref]]\n  states:      [c1_v]\n  derivs:      [der_c1_v]\n  inputs:      [Vin]\n  outputs:     [Vcap]\n  initial:     [[c1_v,0]]\n  residuals:\n     -r1_p_i-r1_n_i  = 0\n     r1_i-r1_p_i  = 0\n     r1_v-r1_p_v+r1_n_v  = 0\n     r1_T_heatPort-r1_T  = 0\n     r1_R_actual-r1_R*((r1_T_heatPort-r1_T_ref)*r1_alpha+1)  = 0\n     r1_v-r1_R_actual*r1_i  = 0\n     r1_LossPower-r1_i*r1_v  = 0\n     -c1_p_i-c1_n_i  = 0\n     c1_i-c1_p_i  = 0\n     c1_v-c1_p_v+c1_n_v  = 0\n     c1_i-c1_C*der_c1_v  = 0\n     gnd_p_v  = 0\n     src_v-src_p_v+src_n_v  = 0\n     -src_p_i-src_n_i  = 0\n     src_i-src_p_i  = 0\n     src_v-Vin  = 0\n     Vcap-c1_v  = 0\n     src_p_i+r1_p_i  = 0\n     r1_n_i+c1_p_i  = 0\n     src_n_i+gnd_p_i+c1_n_i  = 0\n     src_p_v-r1_p_v  = 0\n     r1_n_v-c1_p_v  = 0\n     c1_n_v-gnd_p_v  = 0\n     gnd_p_v-src_n_v  = 0"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "Notice the residuals: 23 of them, including the connector-flattened currents and voltages (`r1_p_i`, `c1_p_v`, etc.). The `R_actual` and `LossPower` come from MSL's `ConditionalHeatPort` — built into MSL's resistor for thermal coupling, but with `useHeatPort = false` it stays decoupled and just contributes a constant `T_heatPort = T_ref`. We get all of that for free.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 3. Same dynamics as the hand-rolled version\n\nLinearise around the equilibrium and verify the matrices match `examples/RCFilter.mo`:",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "[A, B, C, D] : mod_state_space(m_msl, [c1_v = 0, Vin = 0])$\nprint(\"A =\")$ A;\nprint(\"B =\")$ B;\nprint(\"C =\")$ C;\nprint(\"D =\")$ D;",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 54,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "A =\nmatrix([-2.0])\nB =\nmatrix([2.0])\nC =\nmatrix([1.0])\nD ="
          ]
        },
        {
          "data": {
            "text/latex": [
              "\\ifx\\endpmatrix\\undefined\\pmatrix{\\else\\begin{pmatrix}\\fi 0.0\\cr\\ifx\\endpmatrix\\undefined}\\else\\end{pmatrix}\\fi "
            ]
          },
          "execution_count": 54,
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "execute_result"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "$A = -2$, $B = 2$, $C = 1$, $D = 0$ — exactly the matrices we got from the hand-rolled `RCFilter.mo` in `01_linear_analysis.macnb`. With $R = 1$ and $C = 0.5$, $A = -1/(RC) = -2$ and $B = 1/(RC) = 2$. Same plant, expressed via standard library components.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 4. Step response\n\nDC gain $= -CA^{-1}B + D = 1$, so a unit step settles at 1.0:",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "[t_step, y_step] : mod_step(m_msl, [c1_v = 0, Vin = 0], 5.0)$\n\nax_draw2d(\n  color=\"blue\", line_width=2, name=\"Vcap(t) — MSL-built RC\",\n  lines(t_step, y_step),\n  color=\"black\", dash=\"dot\", explicit(1, t, 0, 5),\n  title=\"Step response of RCFilterMSL\",\n  xlabel=\"t (s)\", ylabel=\"Vcap (V)\",\n  grid=true, showlegend=true\n)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 55,
      "outputs": [
        {
