    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "The 3×3 A matrix is dense — every state couples to the others through the feedback path. There are no inputs left at the top level (the setpoint is internal, fed by the `Step` source via `setpoint.y → fb.u1`), so B is empty; same for C, D since no `output Real` is declared.\n\nClosed-loop pole locations are the eigenvalues of A:",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "[eigvals, eigvecs] : np_eig(ndarray(float(A_pid)))$\nnp_to_list(eigvals);",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 60,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "text/latex": [
              "\\left[ -110.18316306162187 , 0.9949548970401114\\,i-0.9084184691890487 , -\\left(0.9949548970401114\\,i\\right)-0.9084184691890487 \\right] "
            ]
          },
          "execution_count": 60,
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "execute_result"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "Three poles: one fast real pole around $-110$ (that's the derivative-filter dynamics, with $T_D = T_d / N_d = 0.01$, giving $-1/T_D = -100$), and a complex conjugate pair around $-0.91 \\pm 0.99j$ — the dominant closed-loop dynamics, slightly underdamped, $\\zeta \\approx 0.67$. All in the left half-plane: stable closed loop.\n\nThat's the workflow this notebook was meant to demonstrate: take an MSL plant, wrap it in an MSL controller, get the linearised state-space to do classical analysis (poles, Bode, Nyquist), and feed it into whatever control-design tools you like.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## What we got\n\nmochi reads MSL components transparently. The user just declares them:\n\n```modelica\nModelica.Electrical.Analog.Basic.Resistor r(R = 100);\nModelica.Blocks.Continuous.PID pid(k = 1.0, Ti = 0.5, Td = 0.1);\n```\n\nand rumoca + mochi handle the entire flattening — connector expansion, type-alias resolution (`SI.Resistance`, `SI.Voltage`), parent-class inheritance, parameter-expression evaluation (`D.T = max({Td/Nd, 100*1e-15})`), multi-domain interfaces, parameter-gated `If` branches, the works.\n\nThree plants, all the same dynamics:\n\n- `examples/RCFilter.mo` — hand-rolled connector + components.\n- `examples/extends/RCFilterExtends.mo` — refactored with a `partial model OnePort` base.\n- `examples/msl/RCFilterMSL.mo` — composed from MSL components.\n\nAll three linearise to A = -2, B = 2, C = 1, D = 0. Three different ways to spell the same plant. The MSL version is the one most working control engineers will reach for first: standard names, professionally maintained, multi-domain, full unit checking, hooks for thermal coupling and loss-power output.\n\nWhat this unlocks:\n\n- Use the right physical component out of MSL's 1500+ catalogue.\n- Multi-domain modelling (electrical-mechanical-thermal-fluid) without writing the bridge components yourself.\n- Closed-loop design with MSL's `Modelica.Blocks.Continuous.{P, PI, PID, LimPID}` and friends — load, linearise, design, simulate, all in mochi.",
      "metadata": {}
    }
  ]
}